definition.value: A monosaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a heptose.
A monosaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a hexose.
An aldohexose derivative that has D-configuration.
A hexose derivative that is formally obtained from a ketohexose.
A monosaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a ketoaldonic acid.
A monosaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a pentose.
A monosaccharide that is formally obtained from a uronic acid.
A carbohydrate derivative that is formally obtained from an alditol.
An alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a glycosyl alditol.
A glycosyl alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a galactosylglycerol.
A glycosyl alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a glucosylglycerol.
A glycosyl alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a glycosyl glycerol.
An alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a pentitol.
A carbohydrate derivative that is formally obtained from a carbohydrate acid.
A sulfur-containing amino acid whose alpha-carboxylic acid group is ionized (not protonated).
An aromatic amino acid whose alpha-carboxylic acid group is ionized (non-protonated).
A monocarboxylic acid that consists of phenylacetic acid bearing bromo, hydroxy and nitro substituents at position 3, 4 and 5 respectively.
An azide carrying a (3-bromo-4-hydroxy-5-nitrophenyl)acetyl substituent.
An N-acylamino acid that consists of 6-aminohexanoic acid bearing an N-(3-bromo-4-hydroxy-5-nitrophenyl)acetyl substituent.
A transition element cation that is a form of platinum having had electrons removed resulting in the 2+, 3+, or 4+ cation.
A carboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of a carbohydrate acid derivative.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion that is formally obtained from a ketoaldonate.
A carbohydrate derivative that is formally obtained from an oligosaccharide.
An oligosaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a hexasaccharide.
An oligosaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a pentasaccharide.
An oligosaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a tetrasaccharide.
A tunaxanthin that consists of epsilon,epsilon-carotene bearing hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 3' (the 3S,3'S,6S,6'S-diastereomer).
An oligosaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a trisaccharide.
A synthetic galactosylfructose disaccharide used in the treatment of constipation and hepatic encephalopathy.
An optically active form of ofloxacin having (S)-configuration; an inhibitor of bacterial topoisomerase IV and DNA gyrase

A quinolone that consits of 4-oxo-1,4-dihydroquinoline-3-carboxylic acid bearing a cyclopropyl substituent at position 1, a fluoro substitiuent at position 6, a (4aS,7aS)-octahydro-6H-pyrrolo[3,4-b]pyridin-6-yl group at position 7 and a methoxy substituent at position 8. A member of the fluoroquinolone class of antibacterial agents.

A carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of (S)-2-methylbutyric acid with the hydroxy group adjacent to the ring junction of (3R,5R)-7-[(1S,2S,6S,8S,8aR)-6,8-dihydroxy-2-methyl-1,2,6,7,8,8a-hexahydronaphthalen-1-yl]-3,5-dihydroxyheptanoic acid. Derived from microbial transformation of mevastatin, pravastatin is a reversible inhibitor of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coenzyme A (HMG-CoA). The sodium salt is used for lowering cholesterol and preventing cardiovascular disease. It is one of the lower potency statins, but has the advantage of fewer side effects compared with lovastatin and simvastatin.

Benzophenone substituted on one of the phenyl rings at C-3 and C-4 by hydroxy groups and at C-5 by a nitro group, and on the other phenyl ring by a methyl group at C-4. It is an inhibitor of catechol O-methyltransferase.
A polysaccharide composed of beta-(1->3)-linked glucose residues containing sporadic beta-(1->6)-linkages as branch points or inter-residue linkages and 2-3% D-mannitol at some reducing termini.
An aldehyde hydrate resulting from the addition of water to the aldehyde group of abietal.
A sodium salt that is the disodium salt of succinic acid. The hexahydrate form is used as an ingredient of topical preparations for the treatment of cataract.
A hydrate that is the hexahydrate form of sodium succinate. It is used as an ingredient of topical preparations for the treatment of cataract.
Any organic heterobicyclic compound containing ortho-fused pyrrolidine and piperidine rings.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of anhydrous tenovir.

An organic sodium salt that is the heptahydrate form of pemetrexed disodium. Inhibits thymidylate synthase (TS), 421 dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR), and glycinamide ribonucleotide formyltransferase (GARFT).
Any alcohol in which two hydroxy groups are bonded to the same atom.
A 1,1-diol resulting from the formal addition of water to the carbonyl group of a aldehyde.
A 1,1-diol resulting from the formal addition of water to the carbonyl group of a ketone.
A monohydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of 3-hydroxy-4-methoxybenzoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A methoxybenzoic acid that is 4-methoxybenzoic acid bearing a hydroxy substituent at position 3.
A amidobenzoic acid that consists of salicylic acid bearing an acetamido substituent at position 4.
An amidobenzoate that is the conjugate base of 4-acetamidosalicylic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1-alkyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-alkyl group is specified as hexadecyl.
An organic sodium salt that is the monohydrate form of sulfacetamide sodium.
A primary alcohol that is pentan-1-ol bearing an additional methyl substituent at position 4.
